"This document presents an FPGA implementation and comparative analysis of various 16-bit high-performance adder architectures, conducted by students from the Indian Institute of Information Technology Vadodara. Adders are fundamental components in digital systems, significantly impacting processor and arithmetic unit performance, as well as overall system speed and latency.\n\nThe study focuses on four distinct 16-bit adder architectures: the Ripple Carry Adder (RCA), a Carry Lookahead-style Adder (CLA), the Kogge-Stone Adder (KSA), and an FPGA-optimized behavioral adder. The designs were implemented using Verilog HDL and synthesized on a Nexys A7 FPGA using the Vivado tool suite. A unified testbench was employed to ensure functional correctness under identical conditions, while performance was evaluated based on propagation delay and resource utilization.\n\nThe paper highlights the inherent trade-offs between delay and hardware usage on FPGA platforms. The **Ripple Carry Adder (RCA)**, characterized by its simplicity and low cost, suffers from linear delay due to its sequential carry propagation, making it less suitable for high-performance applications. The **Carry Lookahead-style Adder (CLA)** improves upon RCA by introducing generate and propagate signals for more efficient carry logic organization. However, in the specific implementation presented, the carry propagation remains sequential, limiting its performance gains.\n\nTo overcome the limitations of RCA for high-performance needs, more advanced architectures like the **Kogge-Stone Adder (KSA)**, a type of Parallel Prefix Adder, were investigated. KSA utilizes a tree-like structure for parallel carry computation, significantly reducing delay to O(log\u2082N). While offering superior speed, KSA comes with increased hardware complexity and routing challenges.\n\nThe **FPGA-optimized behavioral adder** leverages high-level arithmetic expressions. This approach allows FPGA synthesis tools to automatically map the design onto dedicated, highly optimized carry-chain hardware, often resulting in competitive or superior performance compared to manually designed architectures, with a simpler design.\n\nThe comparative analysis, summarized in a table of architecture trade-offs, reveals that while KSA offers the lowest theoretical delay due to its parallel computation, the FPGA-optimized behavioral adder frequently demonstrates competitive or even better practical performance on the FPGA. This is attributed to the synthesis tool's ability to exploit dedicated FPGA carry-chain structures. The study also notes that FPGA-specific features like these dedicated carry chains significantly influence the practical performance of different adder architectures, sometimes even improving the performance of simpler designs like RCA.\n\nThe experimental setup involved RTL elaboration, simulation, synthesis, pin assignment, implementation, and timing analysis. Input values were stabilized using registered flip-flops, and FPGA switches and push buttons were mapped to operands and control signals, with outputs displayed on LEDs.\n\nFuture work suggested includes implementing other parallel prefix adders, investigating power consumption, and further optimizing the Kogge-Stone adder. The authors acknowledge support from their professors and institution."